<TITLE> BB snubs IMF on policy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 6 (bdnews24.com)  Central bank governor Salehuddin Ahmed said Sunday Bangladesh would make a monetary policy on its ownnot under pressure from the International Monetary Fund. "We will make our monetary policy on our own for development of the country," the central banker told reporters after a meeting with the visiting IMF delegation. Thomas Rumbaugh, IMF adviser for Asia and Pacific Department, led the five-member delegation to the meeting with the Bangladesh Bank governor at the central bank headquarters. Salehuddin said the monetary policy for July-December would be designed to control inflation, boost growth and cut poverty. "Inflation is a major global challenge." The BB governor said the IMF delegation voiced concern over inflation in Bangladesh and prescribed some suggestions to rein in inflation. "We told them that we would make a policy on our own to face the challenge of inflation. We hope it would yield good results," Salehuddin said. A senior Bangladesh Bank official, asking not to named, told bdnews24.com that the monetary policy for July-December would be announced soon. bdnews
